<div id="new_ris2" class="modal bd-example-modal-lg" tabindex="-1" role="dialog" aria-labelledby="myLargeModalLabel" aria-hidden="true">
  <div class="modal-dialog modal-lg">
    <div class="modal-content">
    <div class="modal-header">
            <h5 class="modal-title" id="exampleModalLongTitle">Welcome to RIS 2.0</h5>
            <button type="button" class="btn btn-warning" data-dismiss="modal" aria-label="Close">
              <span aria-hidden="true">&times;</span>
            </button>
          </div>
      <div class="modal-body">
               <p>The biggest difference is that the RIS 2.0 focuses on&nbsp;<em>targets</em>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<em>indicators</em>, i.e. what is to be achieved, and how to measure progress towards that objective. An obvious example is a national target to increase marine protected area coverage from 3% to 12% by 2020, with an accompanying indicator of percentage protected area coverage. At a site level, there could be targets linked to protected area management plans. We have built a framework to allow users to specify their own targets like this in the RIS, and to identify the most appropriate indicators and associated data, whether at global, regional, national or site level. The RIS already has a few examples that we have pre-loaded, but ultimately it will be for the BIOPAMA community to build up this target/indicator repository, which will become an increasingly important role for the BIOPAMA Regional Observatories across the ACP to support.</p>

<p>Thanks to some technical wizardry, we've managed to get the RIS to serve up more and richer data, faster than before. This was very important as we have many users who do not have super-fast internet access, and we didn't want to strip down the content and functionality. Instead, we spent a lot of time figuring out how to best structure the system to only load the necessary data, and to use modern technology such as vector tiles to deliver great looking, performant maps. There's more detail on this in the section “Techie Corner”, if you want to delve into this and find out how it is revolutionising mapping on the internet.</p>

<p>For now, we are releasing the system for people to try, and give us feedback. We will be able to make design changes, add new features and adapt the flow of information based on your input. In the current release, we can work directly with you to set up new targets and indicators, whereas in the future you, and others like you, should be able to do this independently. Please contact us as indicated below if you wish to define specific targets and measures for protected areas in your region – we can do this together.</p>

<p>The site design is now in line with the parent site&nbsp;<a href="https://www.biopama.org">www.biopama.org</a>, where you can find out all about the BIOPAMA programme which we implement together with the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN).</p>

<p>Our base maps are much improved, with contributions from&nbsp;<a href="https://www.mapbox.com">MapBox</a>&nbsp;and of course updated reference data from the&nbsp;<a href="https://protectedplanet.net">World Database on Protected Areas (© UNEP-WCMC)</a>. Clicking on any region/country/site will automatically zoom you to that area, and information and links relevant for that level will appear. Regions, countries and sites all have dedicated pages that present the summary information.</p>

<p>BIOPAMA RIS features a suite of standard indicators and metrics from another great resource developed here at JRC, the&nbsp;<a href="https://dopa-explorer.jrc.ec.europa.eu">Digital Observatory for Protected Areas (DOPA)</a>. DOPA is a global system, and differs from RIS in that it is based on harmonised global data that is processed automatically for 30000 protected areas worldwide – that's all protected areas larger than 25km2, which represent over 95% of the total surface area which is defined as protected. You can link easily from RIS to DOPA to check out the country and site level reports, plus you can use DOPA to explore data for all the non-ACP countries. The DOPA Explorer Version 3.0 is the latest version of the tool. Invisible to the user, behind the scenes the RIS and DOPA exchange information through so-called REST services (again, more technical details about this framework are available in Techie Corner if you are interested).&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p>For more detail on using the RIS and its specific functions, check out the “How To” section on the main page.</p>

<p>Don't forget you can join in the conversation on BIOPAMA at our&nbsp;<a href="https://www.yammer.com/biopama">Yammer group</a>&nbsp;– registering is quick and easy and you can interact with hundreds of protected area professionals worldwide.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h3>Techie Corner</h3>

<h4>Vector Tiles</h4>

<p>Vector tiles are packets of geographic data, packaged into pre-defined roughly-square shaped "tiles" for transfer over the web. This is different to the more established method of pre-rendered raster map tiles (delivered as image files), but has the advantage of being faster (less data are transferred) and styling (colours, symbols) is done on the client, which gives full flexibility as opposed to pre-defined styles. Also, since the data are in a vector format, geometric operations (clipping, intersection, query etc) can be done client-side, allowing the user to interact directly with map features. MapBox is a leading proponent of this technology, and there are several tools available for serving up vector tiles from spatial data sources and for rendering the data in web clients.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<h4>REST services</h4>

<p>REST stands for&nbsp;Representational State Transfer, and are interoperable web services that support simple requests to deliver payloads of data as HTML, XML, JSON or other formats.</p>

<p>Because these types of services are so modular, and independent of underlying tools, we decided a few years ago to make them the basis of our systems architecture. In particular, they provide access to our databases from our web clients, serving up queries to get lists of protected areas or species, without having to define long SQL queries.</p>

<p>You can find a free tutorial illustrating our approach to setting up and using REST services at https://github.com/lucageo/foss4g</p>
